  <text>
    <body><div type="letter">
      <p>Esher Monday 1 o'clock</p>
      <p>Dearest W. Tho' I left Hester in charge to write to you, yet dearest Mate, I must send a line to you from here; for I am sure it will give you pleasure; &amp; I find things to answer in your 2 dear long interesting letters, which I have been</p>
      <p>reading in my way down here. Yes-- I will certainly go to another Drawing-Room. I had intended doing so at any rate probably; but to please you is ample reason, had I not even thought of it otherwise.</p>
      <p>You shall hear &amp; know all about my dress &amp; everything.--</p>
      <p>How stiff &amp; odd is J. Fortescue's letter!--</p>
      <p>Dear Mate, I</p>
      <p>hope for great ultimate success in the musical &amp; dramatic line,-- but only as the result of hard study, &amp; real solid work, &amp; also if undertaken in the right spirit; not from vanity, but from far deeper &amp; higher feelings.</p>
      <p>And for the present, I cannot hope to shine at all of course. But indeed I value your wise &amp; excellent counsels;</p>
      <p>&amp; will always endeavour to bear in mind the dangers of trusting to mere flash &amp; transient success or gratification of vanity. Altho' I think I have too real &amp; true a soul to be hit with such.-- No time for more.</p>
    </div></body>
